1 (d) To increase funding for school districts in a way that results
2 in direct property tax relief, which means a dollar-for-dollar
3 replacement of property taxes by a state funding source;
4 (e) To provide funding for a grant program created by the
5 Legislature to address teacher and paraeducator turnover rates and keep
6 existing teachers and paraeducators in classrooms;
7 (f) To provide funding to increase career and technical educational
8 classroom opportunities for students, including, but not limited to,
9 computer science education. Such funding must provide students with the
10 academic and technical skills, knowledge, and training necessary to
11 succeed in future careers;
12 (g) To provide funding for a grant program created by the
13 Legislature to provide students the opportunity to have a mentor who will
14 continuously engage with the student directly to aid in the student's
15 professional growth and give ongoing support and encouragement to the
16 student;
17 (h) To provide funding for extraordinary increases in special
18 education expenditures to allow school districts with large, unexpected
19 special education expenditures to more easily meet the needs of all
20 students;
21 (i) To provide funding to help recruit teachers throughout the state
22 by utilizing apprenticeships through a teacher apprenticeship program and
23 an alternative certification process;
24 (j) To provide funding to develop and implement a professional
25 learning system to help provide sustained professional learning and
26 training regarding evidence-based reading instruction and for a grant
27 program relating to dyslexia research; and
28 (k) To provide funding for a pilot project administered by the State
29 Department of Education to provide menstrual products to school
30 districts.
